WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.880
Today I'm giving a webinar on Interactivity in Production. This webinar is the third in

00:00:12.880 --> 00:00:18.620
a three-part series that we've been doing. Last month, Garrett Grollman delivered Reproducibility

00:00:18.620 --> 00:00:25.879
in Production, and Thomas Mock delivered RStudio Connect in Production. Those are freely available

00:00:25.879 --> 00:00:32.080
on demand at resources.rstudio.com, the same place this one will be made available. But before

00:00:32.080 --> 00:00:38.040
jumping into Interactivity in Production, I wanted to acknowledge some of the themes from

00:00:38.040 --> 00:00:44.200
those first two webinars that I'll be touching on as well. The first theme is production means

00:00:44.200 --> 00:00:50.119
different things to different people. Garrett talked about this, Tom talked about this really

00:00:50.119 --> 00:00:56.240
well with RStudio Connect and how the Connect product can meet you where you are and make

00:00:56.240 --> 00:01:03.639
production available in different forms with different meanings to wherever you are in your

00:01:03.639 --> 00:01:11.480
analytics lifecycle. Also along those same lines, RStudio Connect is this publishing platform for

00:01:11.480 --> 00:01:19.080
communicating impactful data science work. Our Markdown is a tool for creating computational

00:01:19.080 --> 00:01:29.680
documents and communicating impactful data science through either static reports or documents that

00:01:29.680 --> 00:01:35.680
have interactive elements inside them. And the one thing that I want to use as a jumping-off

00:01:35.680 --> 00:01:42.199
point for starting our discussion today is what Garrett introduced in the reproducibility webinar,

00:01:42.760 --> 00:01:51.480
which was the interactivity spectrum. So in this interactivity spectrum, Garrett made this case for

00:01:51.480 --> 00:01:58.120
thinking strategically about what level of interactivity your data product actually requires

00:01:58.120 --> 00:02:03.400
and meeting that level of interactivity with the type of experience that you want to deliver in

00:02:03.400 --> 00:02:10.919
order to communicate effectively. So I really like this a lot, but it does kind of presuppose that

00:02:10.919 --> 00:02:17.160
you know what you want to build in the first place or you're at a point in your iterative

00:02:17.160 --> 00:02:24.199
development work cycle where you're willing to do some introspection on what you should or could be

00:02:24.199 --> 00:02:33.559
building. This is important because as you progress down the interactivity hierarchy, things become

00:02:33.559 --> 00:02:40.279
more complicated to build, and we tend to think of Shiny applications, the highest level of

00:02:40.279 --> 00:02:48.199
interactivity, as the most complex to develop. Now on the other side of things, Garrett also

00:02:48.199 --> 00:02:55.000
spoke to this in his webinar. We tend to see people learn Shiny and then use it for just a lot of

00:02:55.000 --> 00:03:01.399
things, borderline on everything. And I know I've done this, and it's very hard once you commit to

00:03:01.399 --> 00:03:08.919
this Shiny application workflow or development cycle to walk back from Shiny. In other words,

00:03:08.919 --> 00:03:14.360
once you've committed to using Shiny, it's difficult to take a step back and evaluate

00:03:14.360 --> 00:03:20.440
whether you would be better served delivering your desired user experience in another format.

00:03:22.360 --> 00:03:29.559
Now all that being said, I love Shiny, so I want to talk about the case for starting with Shiny

00:03:29.559 --> 00:03:37.240
because I know that folks out there do this too. It's a great tool. It makes things

00:03:37.240 --> 00:03:43.880
really easy, and it's a great tool for doing a lot of things like exploratory data analysis,

00:03:43.880 --> 00:03:50.600
prototyping, fast iteration through building tools that other folks might want to use and

00:03:50.600 --> 00:03:55.720
that you can use to drive impact of your data science work inside of your own organization.

00:03:56.679 --> 00:04:02.520
Now I'm no Shiny wizard. You can go and look at the Shiny contest results we ran

00:04:03.160 --> 00:04:08.679
last spring to see evidence of actual Shiny wizardry, but I'm comfortable enough with Shiny

00:04:08.679 --> 00:04:14.279
that I can build really powerful prototypes in a short amount of time, and I know a lot of folks

00:04:14.279 --> 00:04:20.279
are in that same boat. So when I need to build a tool that other people might want to use too,

00:04:20.279 --> 00:04:27.720
my natural inclination is to start developing that tool in Shiny. Now these things can quickly

00:04:27.720 --> 00:04:33.880
escalate when you want to give access to someone else to use that tool, and that's what I want to

00:04:33.880 --> 00:04:45.239
talk about today. I sort of think of starting with Shiny as the equivalent of writing an hour-long

00:04:45.239 --> 00:04:50.519
talk. I call starting with Shiny and local development as the hour-long talk of data

00:04:50.519 --> 00:04:57.720
products, and hour-long talks, if you've ever developed one, can be rambling and cluttered.

00:04:57.720 --> 00:05:02.760
You have a lot of time to work with, so there can be parts that work really well and parts that

00:05:02.760 --> 00:05:08.359
don't work so well, and I know I'm giving an hour-long talk currently, so I hope that in the

00:05:08.359 --> 00:05:13.480
questions you'll let me know which parts work well and which do not so that I can clarify those.

00:05:14.200 --> 00:05:22.040
But the goal is when you're taking this local development asset into production,

00:05:22.040 --> 00:05:29.079
so you want to turn that hour-long talk of data products into the lightning talk of data products.

00:05:29.079 --> 00:05:35.399
So the difference between hour-long talks and lightning talks, our lightning talks are these

00:05:35.399 --> 00:05:41.959
targeted, really elegant, streamlined little pockets of information that you're trying to

00:05:41.959 --> 00:05:49.320
deliver in a very short amount of time, and the irony is that it can take a lot more time of your

00:05:49.320 --> 00:05:54.920
own to develop a lightning talk than it can to develop an hour-long talk where you have a lot

00:05:54.920 --> 00:06:01.320
of space to work with, because those lightning talks, they just need to have that streamline,

00:06:01.320 --> 00:06:08.519
that concision. You need to get to your message effectively and conclude everything in the right

00:06:08.519 --> 00:06:16.519
amount of time. So maybe you start with Shiny in local development, and by the end, maybe in

00:06:16.519 --> 00:06:24.279
production, that original Shiny application you had on your local machine looks very different.

00:06:24.279 --> 00:06:30.119
Maybe once you get to production, it's a group of assets that complement each other. Maybe it's a

00:06:30.119 --> 00:06:36.200
very different kind of Shiny application. As long as you're evaluating along the way, starting with

00:06:36.200 --> 00:06:45.480
Shiny in the hierarchy of interactivity is really okay by me. So this is my agenda for the webinar

00:06:45.480 --> 00:06:53.640
discussion today. I started with making a case for starting with Shiny, and now I want to talk about

00:06:53.640 --> 00:07:00.200
when you're taking a prototype of a Shiny application into production, what I consider

00:07:00.200 --> 00:07:06.839
the most important thing is. And this is my perspective as a solutions engineer at RStudio.

00:07:07.399 --> 00:07:12.440
Then I want to talk about Joe Chang's most important thing for Shiny in production.

00:07:12.440 --> 00:07:23.079
Joe is, if you aren't familiar, the CTO of RStudio, and he was the creator of the Shiny package.

00:07:24.040 --> 00:07:30.040
After that, I want to talk about an example, a prototype app that I built, and then went through

00:07:30.040 --> 00:07:36.119
steps that Joe outlines in his performance workflow to take that application into production.

00:07:36.119 --> 00:07:41.160
And along the way, I'm going to show you what steps I took to refactor, and then evaluate the

00:07:41.160 --> 00:07:47.160
impact of that application, and finally reconsider the hierarchy of interactivity for what I've

00:07:47.559 --> 00:07:55.720
produced. So let's jump right into it. This is what I consider the most important thing

00:07:55.720 --> 00:08:03.160
for running Shiny in production, and that is you need to have a sandbox publishing environment as

00:08:03.160 --> 00:08:10.600
part of your development infrastructure. This thing right here, you need it. It should be a

00:08:10.600 --> 00:08:18.200
place where you can publish freely into a server that is ideally configured to be an identical twin

00:08:18.200 --> 00:08:24.040
of your production server, and this is your testing ground. You can call it a sandbox,

00:08:24.040 --> 00:08:32.119
staging, test server, whatever. You need one of these. If you only have one server at your

00:08:32.119 --> 00:08:40.280
disposal, in a pinch, even something like this can work. You can have the same piece of content

00:08:40.280 --> 00:08:48.119
be published to two different destinations on a single RStudio Connect box, and have one

00:08:48.119 --> 00:08:56.039
destination be reserved for production, while the other destination is reserved for testing, staging.

00:08:57.320 --> 00:09:05.080
If you need any help at all in your journey to production advocating for the right

00:09:05.080 --> 00:09:10.280
analytic infrastructure, please reach out to us at solutions.rstudio.com,

00:09:10.280 --> 00:09:16.520
where there are a bunch of resources for having these conversations, or community.rstudio.com

00:09:16.520 --> 00:09:21.479
in the R admins channel, and that's where a lot of us on solutions engineering like to hang out

00:09:21.479 --> 00:09:28.359
and answer questions coming from the community, so two great resources there. So that was my

00:09:28.359 --> 00:09:33.960
most important thing. Joe has a very different perspective, and it's equally valid, so these are

00:09:33.960 --> 00:09:41.400
two awesome opinions, but Joe's shiny in production, most important thing, he highlights in this

00:09:41.400 --> 00:09:50.119
excellent talk that he gave at RStudio Conf 2019, which is also available at resources.rstudio.com

00:09:50.119 --> 00:09:57.799
slash webinars for you to watch. This talk is excellent, and this is your homework from

00:09:57.799 --> 00:10:03.960
this webinar, is to go watch Joe's talk if you haven't seen it already, because it is really

00:10:03.960 --> 00:10:11.080
that impactful if you are doing anything that involves Shiny in production. So this talk was

00:10:11.080 --> 00:10:17.080
the keynote where he introduced the tools that our Shiny engineering team here at RStudio

00:10:17.080 --> 00:10:23.640
has been working on to help support bringing Shiny into production. So it starts with

00:10:24.200 --> 00:10:32.359
going through Shiny test, Shiny load test, profvis, plot caching, and async, and he highlighted

00:10:32.359 --> 00:10:38.520
a couple of these tools throughout his talk, but the thing that's most important to Joe is

00:10:39.159 --> 00:10:45.239
profvis for Shiny in production. This is a general profile for R code, but it's

00:10:45.960 --> 00:10:51.880
super important for when you're bringing Shiny applications into production.

00:10:52.840 --> 00:10:59.559
A lot of prototype applications fall over in production because they contain these performance

00:10:59.559 --> 00:11:08.280
anti-patterns, so it's important to, when you're trying to turn a prototype into a production

00:11:08.280 --> 00:11:16.039
application, to ask yourself questions and suss out whether your application is suitable

00:11:16.039 --> 00:11:23.080
for production in its current state. So two questions you can answer that are great is,

00:11:23.080 --> 00:11:31.239
is this app fast enough for production, and then if it's not, what is the cause

00:11:31.960 --> 00:11:38.599
of that performance bottleneck? So through the course of Joe's keynote, he goes through

00:11:38.599 --> 00:11:46.280
and looks at an example application called Cran Whales that he created and covered

00:11:48.359 --> 00:11:55.799
how to make that application faster through the application of these two tools, Shiny load test

00:11:55.799 --> 00:12:05.239
to see if the app is fast enough, and profvis to see what in the R code is making that app

00:12:05.239 --> 00:12:13.479
not fast enough. So he lays out this excellent performance workflow, which is the real gem

00:12:13.479 --> 00:12:20.440
here of this talk. You ask if the app is fast enough, you test to see what's making it slow,

00:12:20.520 --> 00:12:30.840
and then three is you optimize, you solve those problems, and the importance of using profvis is,

00:12:30.840 --> 00:12:37.239
you can tell how passionate Joe is about this when he talks about it in the keynote. He says,

00:12:37.239 --> 00:12:44.359
you know, you cannot guess at what is making your R code slow. You do have to use this profiler

00:12:44.359 --> 00:12:52.599
because your intuition about what is making that code slow, it stinks. It's garbage. It's not good.

00:12:53.880 --> 00:12:59.960
Like, even folks who are very competent at building Shiny applications can get tripped up

00:12:59.960 --> 00:13:07.159
by, you know, simply assuming you know what the problem is. So profvis is an amazing tool

00:13:07.159 --> 00:13:15.880
to help you get to the optimization stage and then make real impactful changes to how your code works.

00:13:19.320 --> 00:13:25.159
So, in the spirit of Joe's talk and his crayon whales application success story, I wanted to build

00:13:25.159 --> 00:13:31.880
a similar application for this webinar, and I won't repeat the performance workflow demo that Joe

00:13:31.960 --> 00:13:38.919
has already done in his. Definitely go watch it. It's really great, seriously. But I wanted to

00:13:38.919 --> 00:13:44.919
create this prototype to start that would realistically highlight some of those same

00:13:44.919 --> 00:13:53.559
or similar performance anti-patterns. So, I have a crayon logs app that's called the trending R

00:13:53.559 --> 00:14:00.919
packages app. And here's what it does. As you can see here in the screenshot, it has this table.

00:14:00.919 --> 00:14:11.000
It's a DT table. And you can see which R packages have been trending over the last period of time.

00:14:12.200 --> 00:14:21.000
Top ten. And then click on each of these applications to view a little bit of metadata

00:14:21.000 --> 00:14:30.119
about what that package is and what it does. So, all of this data is coming from the crayon logs

00:14:30.119 --> 00:14:40.359
API project, plus a little bit of Rvest magic scraping metadata about each package. So, the

00:14:40.359 --> 00:14:47.400
workflow that it goes through is that I call out to the crayon logs API slash trending endpoint to

00:14:47.400 --> 00:14:55.159
get those top ten trending packages. Then I make ten more calls to that crayon logs API to retrieve

00:14:55.159 --> 00:15:02.200
the download counts for each package. Put that data into DT here in the application. And then I

00:15:02.200 --> 00:15:09.719
use Rvest magic to scrape out that metadata about each package when at the point the user clicks on it.

00:15:14.119 --> 00:15:23.559
So, this app, you know, it makes sense to me. I'm constructing this data as I go. I'm not

00:15:23.559 --> 00:15:28.760
thinking about scaling at this point. Works pretty great in my local development environment.

00:15:29.320 --> 00:15:37.479
When I push it to my staging server, it works okay. But I can already tell that there is some

00:15:37.479 --> 00:15:44.520
danger here. As more users come to this application, I'm worried that it won't be

00:15:44.520 --> 00:15:51.479
fast enough to support the number of users that I expect. So, at this point, I think to myself,

00:15:51.479 --> 00:15:57.080
this would be a great case to activate Joe's performance workflow and move through

00:15:57.960 --> 00:16:03.080
shiny load test and profvis to get the answers about whether my application

00:16:03.799 --> 00:16:06.840
is going to work in production and how to fix it so that it does.

00:16:08.599 --> 00:16:17.159
So, I'll spare you the first two points of the workflow. Again, go watch Joe's talk for those.

00:16:17.239 --> 00:16:26.119
And skip to number three where I'm optimizing my code. So, at this point, the number one thing

00:16:26.119 --> 00:16:34.359
that you do very often to optimize some of these performance issues is to move work out of shiny.

00:16:35.000 --> 00:16:41.640
And Joe says there are two important things to consider when you're moving work out of shiny.

00:16:41.640 --> 00:16:47.479
Things that you don't want to do. So, you don't want to do work in shiny while the user is

00:16:47.479 --> 00:16:53.719
waiting. And the second thing is you don't want to do the same work for every user. That's very

00:16:53.719 --> 00:17:01.000
wasteful. So, he had this example of loading the CSV data into a shiny application every time

00:17:01.000 --> 00:17:07.239
a user connects. And this application I actually designed for the purpose of highlighting these

00:17:07.319 --> 00:17:16.839
two anti-patterns. But it does a very similar thing. I am making 11 API requests to the trending

00:17:16.839 --> 00:17:25.560
R packages table to create that data for the user. And then once a user is on the application,

00:17:26.520 --> 00:17:36.520
I'm calling Rvest two times to perform that metadata scraping for each row selection

00:17:36.520 --> 00:17:43.800
that occurs. So, that would be repeating that same work over and over again for every user.

00:17:43.800 --> 00:17:48.920
Which, again, very wasteful. So, how do we solve this problem?

00:17:50.920 --> 00:17:57.719
There are a number of ways I can think of to solve this. I could generate the data ahead of time

00:17:58.280 --> 00:18:06.119
and publish it in the bundle along with my application code. And this is a totally valid

00:18:06.119 --> 00:18:11.239
workflow and makes sense to do for a lot of different types of shiny applications. Sometimes

00:18:11.239 --> 00:18:18.199
you can just pull the data together and throw it in that bundle and send it along as you're

00:18:18.199 --> 00:18:26.199
deploying to staging, to production, and it's fine. The problem here is that I want users to

00:18:26.199 --> 00:18:32.680
see the latest and greatest trending R packages. It's literally an application to explore trends.

00:18:33.239 --> 00:18:40.119
So, I don't want to get stuck manually deploying that new data or cobbling together some sort of

00:18:40.119 --> 00:18:46.680
cron job coupled with a programmatic deployment workflow that I then need to monitor and make

00:18:46.680 --> 00:18:55.160
sure continues to work. I just want new data delivered to my shiny application that users

00:18:55.160 --> 00:19:03.319
can see fresh information about any time they visit the app. So, this is a great case for

00:19:04.839 --> 00:19:12.439
adding R Markdown to the equation. I call this the division of labor. Using R Markdown to create

00:19:13.319 --> 00:19:22.680
an ETL process to put that data together and then host an output file along with that report

00:19:22.680 --> 00:19:30.199
that I can then point my shiny application to consume. So, if you don't know, content deployed

00:19:30.199 --> 00:19:38.359
to an endpoint on RStudio with an R Markdown output metadata output file. In this case,

00:19:38.359 --> 00:19:46.280
in the case of this image, I have this report called report title. Very descriptive. And it

00:19:46.280 --> 00:19:53.479
has an output file that contains this data.csv file. In the course of this report running,

00:19:53.479 --> 00:20:03.479
it creates this data.csv file, writes it out, and then it just gets hosted on RStudio Connect

00:20:03.479 --> 00:20:11.719
alongside my R Markdown report. If I'm running that report on a schedule, that schedule is

00:20:11.719 --> 00:20:19.239
producing this new data.csv file that lives at this web address, and then I can point shiny to

00:20:19.239 --> 00:20:29.959
read in that data from the URL hosted on my Connect server. So, very cool. And that's exactly what I

00:20:29.959 --> 00:20:38.199
want to do for this application in order to move that work out of shiny and do it somewhere else

00:20:38.920 --> 00:20:46.040
so that it doesn't have to be in my shiny code itself. So, this is what I built. My R Markdown

00:20:46.040 --> 00:20:53.479
ETL to generate this same data frame out of the making calls to the trending API and then

00:20:54.280 --> 00:21:02.439
making those RVEST web scraping function calls. And I do this all in an R Markdown document,

00:21:03.000 --> 00:21:09.000
publish that document to Connect, and then I schedule it to run weekly every Friday at a

00:21:09.000 --> 00:21:17.640
certain time. And I can schedule that to run daily or monthly or hourly. Whatever schedule

00:21:17.640 --> 00:21:26.199
I want to produce new data on, I can do that directly in the R Markdown hosted on RStudio

00:21:26.199 --> 00:21:35.239
Connect in the dashboard panel that I'm showing here. So, really, really nifty tool to create

00:21:35.239 --> 00:21:45.400
output data files. So, now I have these three pieces of content here living as my production

00:21:45.959 --> 00:21:52.280
development package. And I'm happy with the performance of my shiny application because I've

00:21:52.280 --> 00:22:00.359
moved that work out of shiny and into this ETL process. So, I have my production assets being

00:22:00.359 --> 00:22:08.119
this ETL in R Markdown, my production application in shiny, which is now fast and doesn't repeat

00:22:08.119 --> 00:22:14.439
work for each user. And then a third asset, which is not really a part of it, but it is fun to

00:22:14.439 --> 00:22:20.920
publish alongside as reference information, which is the Profvis profile for that production

00:22:20.920 --> 00:22:27.719
application. So, all of these three things can live together and be a package that I can

00:22:28.760 --> 00:22:35.800
feel confident about running on my production server and serving my users effectively.

00:22:38.280 --> 00:22:46.119
So, at this point, you know, am I done? Am I making an impact at my organization through what I built?

00:22:46.119 --> 00:22:54.199
How do I answer that question? Is what I built correct? You know, I have these two data products,

00:22:54.199 --> 00:23:00.520
shiny and R Markdown, working harmoniously together. Is there anything else to do?

00:23:01.959 --> 00:23:13.319
So, I'd like to take a stab at trying to quantify or track impact on RStudio Connect with my assets.

00:23:13.319 --> 00:23:20.280
So, how do I know that what I've built is effective at communicating my intended message?

00:23:20.280 --> 00:23:28.839
The whole goal here was to create something useful and to drive users to find, you know,

00:23:28.839 --> 00:23:34.280
insights through this tool or make changes to how we do work at our organization

00:23:35.160 --> 00:23:44.280
through communicating that in shiny and R Markdown. So, am I doing that? Well, there's also

00:23:44.280 --> 00:23:51.400
tools for getting that data off of your RStudio Connect server, and that is through usage of

00:23:51.400 --> 00:23:58.920
another API called the RStudio Connect Instrumentation Data API. And this is a really

00:23:59.000 --> 00:24:05.319
cool feature that Connect has that I think is underutilized. And so, I want to use this talk

00:24:06.359 --> 00:24:13.319
to encourage you to look at some of the resources we currently have for, you know,

00:24:13.319 --> 00:24:18.680
visualizing this type of data on your Connect server, if you have access to a Connect server,

00:24:19.719 --> 00:24:27.479
and explore different variations of building tools that can give you insights into how much

00:24:27.479 --> 00:24:35.319
impact you're actually making through these data products. So, RStudio Connect records

00:24:35.319 --> 00:24:42.040
different types of user activity for different types of content. You've got records for shiny

00:24:42.040 --> 00:24:49.800
applications about each visit to that application and the duration of that visit. And then you have

00:24:50.359 --> 00:24:54.359
records of each visit for static and rendered content.

00:24:56.439 --> 00:25:01.640
This dashboard you see here on the right is one that my colleagues on Solutions at

00:25:01.640 --> 00:25:08.359
Sharing put together called the Connect Usage Dashboard, and it is available at that GitHub URL.

00:25:09.560 --> 00:25:15.000
The code is all there, and we would really encourage you to take that. You can drop it

00:25:15.000 --> 00:25:21.640
into your own server, as is, if you'd like to see this same information about your data products,

00:25:22.280 --> 00:25:28.439
or you can tweak it and make it custom to see or gather information that will answer your own

00:25:28.439 --> 00:25:35.400
questions. I've really been having a fun time lately tweaking this same instrumentation dashboard

00:25:35.400 --> 00:25:40.359
that my colleagues put together and turning it into something that I can answer questions about

00:25:40.359 --> 00:25:48.040
individual apps. So, this is the same dashboard driven by the same helper functions that

00:25:48.040 --> 00:25:54.520
they created, but I've tweaked them just to look at my production application. And I want to know

